Question 6
Why is count++ not thread-safe?
Ideal Answer

count++ is actually three operations:

Read current value
Increment
Write new value

If two threads execute these steps simultaneously, updates can be lost.

Solutions:

synchronized
ReentrantLock
AtomicInteger
Difference

synchronized

Simple
JVM-managed
Automatically releases the lock

ReentrantLock

More flexible
Can use tryLock(), fairness, and interruptible locking
Must unlock manually

AtomicInteger

Lock-free
Uses compare-and-swap (CAS)
Very efficient for simple counters

Which would I choose?

For a simple counter → AtomicInteger
For complex critical sections → ReentrantLock or synchronized
